While I started putting weight on bin 1 on Dec 14, when the crowd was at 5%, I put very little weight on bin 1 in the earlier part of the question, and so will have a terrible Brier score. Once again, the lesson is to allow for a wider range of possibilities in the beginning than might seem reasonable at the time.

Currently, the Baltic Exchange Dry Index is 2,236. The Index appears to be decreasing. Additionally, even if it were to suddenly begin increasing instead, historically the Index rarely increases more than 100 points in one day. Therefore, I am very confident that in 15 hours, the Index will remain lower than 2,500.
Can’t seem to see historical evidence of +10% swings over 2 days or reporting. But reduced volume could mean a heavier swing than usual… leaving 1% in bin2 but vanishingly unlikely.

Only 6 days of trading left. It's already <2500. Historically, it sometimes falls at the end of the year, but it's hard to get a clear picture there. I could picture this going either way (bin 1 or 2), but given that it's already <2500 and that there may be concerns over Omicron, I suppose I'll tilt my forecast slightly in favor of bin 1. And once again, if this question does resolve in bin 1, I will have learned my lesson to assign weights *even* more broadly in the beginning of a question.

The current forecast is for 3100+. On the other hand, it's been sliding a bit lately, but not so precipitously as to induce me to go lower on this Q. (Full disclosure: I am often wrong about such matters, which is one reason why I never actually invest in This Sort Of Thing.)

Since June, the index has been below 2500 only for something like 2 days in Nov, following large swings due to the energy situation in China, which has since stabilized. It's becoming increasingly clear that the index is resuming its trend from before the energy situation in China. I think bin 1 is extremely unlikely at this point, and I think the index will likely be between 4000 and 5000 at the end of the forecast period. It has grown by ~700 to just over 3100 in the past 2 weeks, and with 3 more weeks to go, I suspect it will be in the range of 4000 to 4500 on Dec 24. Because there's so much volatility, I'll leave a lot of weight on bin 2.

Iron ore continues to drag down the capesize index because of energy shortages in China and production cuts in Brazil, but coal pushes it up. Which will win? For now, it's right on the line, but I do think it's likely that the index will go up as the weather gets colder.

It's hard to see the index falling below 2500 in winter, although lower iron ore demand in China is a big factor, too. Moving my forecast up to match the crowd on bin 2, but there's a long time between now and Dec 24, and I suspect things are more likely to move up than down.

Iron ore (not) weighing down capesize.

It's at 3808 now and has been trending down since Oct. 7. China's coal needs apparently made it go up, but their reduced demand for iron ore for steel is making it fall. Which will win by the end of the year? And now even the panamax and supramax indices are falling, too. Given that the trends for nearly all component indices are currently strongly downward and that the current value is just inside bin 2, I'm shifting my forecast more strongly towards the lower bins. I do wonder whether, as the weather gets colder in China, they'll be shipping in more coal. Also, as this index is highly volatile (it has fallen ~1600 (or 1800?) in 19 days), I'm casting my forecast widely among bins.

I expect the underlying trend for the index will be around 7000 to 7500 at the end of the year (largely because of Chinese coal demand), but the index has so much volatility that it's hard to say where it will end up on a particular day. So, I'm casting a wide net around 7k to 7.5k.

This is a great question that examines one important factor underlying economic dislocations in the pandemic. I suspect it's going to get worse before it gets better. The all-time peak was over 11k. I don't think the index could get that high by 24 Dec simply because there isn't enough time, using history as a guide; the 2 previous peaks above 10k took more than the time left in this forecast to reach 10k from where the index is now. An approximate, kluged exponential fit for 2021 predicts about 7.6k by the end of the year. The trouble is, there's so much volatility in this index; in the past month, it has grown by 2k. The index fluctuates by 0.8k within a month routinely.
